      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lawyers for the Poor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Laura K Abel letter disputes August 17 article on reductions by major law firms in free legal services for poor</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Firms Cutting Back on Free Services for Poor'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Legal Firms Cutting Back on Free Services for Poor'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>When Congress slashed the budget of the federal Legal Services Corporation and imposed restrictions on its legal services lawyers, many members of Congress insisted that private resources and the private bar would fill the gap.</p>
        <p>This was never true; federal financing, other financing and pro bono have never met more than 30 percent of the legal needs of the poor. The drop in pro bono hours means that the situation is worse than ever.</p>
        <p>It is time for Congress to restore financing for the Legal Services Corporation and end the restrictions on federally financed legal services lawyers.</p>
        <p>LAURA K. ABEL  New York, Aug. 18, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a staff lawyer at the Brennan Center for Justice, New York University School of Law.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
